{
  "texts": [
    "The claim about the rational kernel follows from combining Theorem 2.8 with Theorem 5.1 to see that the induced maps on the level of vertical kernels in the above diagram are all isomorphisms and the observation of Theorem 3.5 that the idempotent 𝑒 𝑑 is a rational multiple of [𝑑].",
    "□ Splitting rational excisive functorsThe Goodwillie-Burnside ring 𝐴 Q (Epi ≤𝑑) associated to the category Epi ≤𝑑 is equivalent to the endomorphism ring of the unit (Theorem 5.1), so the splitting of the Goodwillie-Burnside ring (Theorem 2.4) will induce the required splitting of the category of rational 𝑑-excisive functors (Theorem 6.4).The idempotents in the Goodwillie-Burnside ring lift to idempotents in the ∞-category of 𝑑excisive functors by applying [Lur17, Lemma 1.2.4.6, Warning 1.2.4.8] and observing that the idempotents in the Goodwillie-Burnside ring are also idempotents in the homotopy category of 𝑑-excisive functors (Theorem 5.2).Given an idempotent 𝑒 in a stable ∞-category C, the ∞-categorical enhancement of work of the first author [Bar09, Theorem 4.4] provides a splitting of C into orthogonal piecesC ≃ 𝐿 𝑒 C × 𝐿 1-𝑒 C,by localizing with respect to the action of the idempotent 𝑒 and the orthogonal idempotent 1 -𝑒.",
    "Since the ∞-category of 𝑑-excisive functors is equivalent to modules over the monoidal unit [ABHS25, Proposition 2.35], the orthogonal idempotent splitting corresponding to 𝑒 𝑑 may be equivalently phrased asExc 𝑑 * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q ≃ Mod Q (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S) ≃ Mod Q (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S [𝑒 -1 𝑑]) × Mod Q (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S [(1 -𝑒 𝑑) -1]), see e.g., [Mat16,May01], where Mod Q (-) is shorthand notation for the ∞-category of modules in the rational functor category Fun * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q.Consider the fibre sequence (1) 𝐷 𝑑 (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S) -→ 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S -→ 𝑃 𝑑-1 (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S) defining the 𝑑-homogeneous layer of the monoidal unit of the ∞-category of 𝑑-excisive functors.",
    "Given a self map 𝑒: 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S → 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S, we obtain a commutative diagram𝐷 𝑑 (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S) 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S 𝑃 𝑑-1 (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S) 𝐷 𝑑 (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S) 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S 𝑃 𝑑-1 (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S) 𝐷 𝑑 (𝑒) 𝑒 𝑃 𝑑 -1 (𝑒)since (leaving inclusions implicit) the left horizontal maps are the counit of the adjunction between 𝑑-homogeneous functors and 𝑑-excisive functors, while the right horizontal maps are the unit of the adjunction between 𝑑-excisive functors and (𝑑 -1)-excisive functors.",
    "Hence, any idempotent 𝑒 of 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S acts by 𝐷 𝑑 (𝑒) on the 𝑑-homogeneous layer and 𝑃 𝑑-1 (𝑒) on the (𝑑 -1)excisive approximation."
  ]
}